import @html {table}
import @styles/docs {navbar, section, theme_head, codeblock}

page_title #= "Codebase documentation"
page_description #= "Internal compiler and build-system references for maintainers and curious readers."
page_head #= theme_head

#[navbar]

#[section, $md:
    @../ (Docs) / Codebase documentation

    # Codebase documentation

    This part of the documentation is for maintainers or anyone curious about the internal structure of Beanstalk's compiler and build system.

    It provides a peek behind the curtain at how Beanstalk works under the hood.
]

#[section, $md:
    ## Explore the codebase

    - @./compiler-design (Compiler design): staged pipeline, task-reading matrix and cross-cutting contracts
    - @./memory-management (Memory management): GC semantics, shared access, borrow validation, ownership and backend lowering
    - @./style-guide (Codebase development standards): implementation style, test strategy and validation gates
    - @./design-scope (Design scope): accepted mechanisms, constraints and intentionally excluded complexity
    - @./language (Compiler-facing language reference): bridge to the canonical language overview
    - @../progress (Progress matrix): current implementation status and known gaps
    - @https://github.com/nyejames/beanstalk/blob/main/docs/roadmap/roadmap.md (Roadmap): planned work and design direction
    - @https://github.com/nyejames/beanstalk/blob/main/index.md (Repository index): quick module and file locator
]

#[section, $md:
    ## Compiler flow

    [codeblock, $code("text"):
        project files
            -> Stage 0: project structure and source discovery
            -> Stage 1: tokenization
            -> Stage 2: header parsing
            -> Stage 3: dependency sorting
            -> Stage 4: AST construction
            -> Stage 5: HIR generation
            -> Stage 6: borrow validation
            -> Stage 7: backend lowering
            -> output files
    ]
]

#[section, $md:
    ## Design docs vs current support

    Codebase pages describe accepted end-state architecture. Some pages define design that the compiler and backends are still converging on.

    Use the @../progress (progress matrix) to see what is implemented, partial, experimental or still missing. Use the @https://github.com/nyejames/beanstalk/blob/main/docs/roadmap/roadmap.md (roadmap) for sequencing and proposals not yet accepted as design.
]
